{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T15-55-31-280Z","slug":"guerrilla-types-in-typescript","locale":"fr","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T15:55:47.545Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2023-09-06--guerrilla-types-in-typescript/index.md","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2023-09-06--guerrilla-types-in-typescript/fr/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/guerrilla-types-in-typescript/fr/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T15-55-31-280Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"c2f0a14365c2ad02d70065dde84033235a34d78f26479923287fc5368504bb85","outputHash":"a31030640f1eb9f5828d33673dd246f5b519b5437a65db7e3422bb120ebdcf4d","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that TypeScript type design can be both **clear** and **DRY** by combining a “big‑picture” primary interface with derived sub‑types, rather than choosing between a monolithic object or a proliferation of named interfaces. It first contrasts the **single large object** (explicit but repetitive) with **multiple named types** (reusable but harder to read), then presents three “guerrilla” techniques:  \n\n1. **Why not all** – define a comprehensive top‑level interface and extract sub‑types via indexed access (`ProductDetails[\"seller\"]`, etc.), keeping documentation in one place while avoiding duplication.  \n2. **Mix‑ins** – compose reusable field groups into logical objects, leveraging TypeScript’s intersection types and utility types.  \n3. **Namespaces** – organize related types under a shared namespace for clearer import/export and real‑world module structure.  \n\nThe tone is a practical tutorial with a light‑hearted, “guerrilla” metaphor, aimed at front‑end and back‑end developers who model semi‑structured API data and want predictable, maintainable TypeScript interfaces.","totalInputTokens":10402,"totalOutputTokens":3274,"totalCacheReadTokens":2048,"total